column18:
Nature of the study. You are invited to participate in a study in which you will be asked to rate questions considering if they can be best answered by a voice assistant (such as Siri and Alexa) or an adult. After the study, we will ask you to provide some basic demographic information. The session should last around 30 minutes. 

 

Compensation. You will be paid $3 for your participation. This study contains attention checks to make sure that participants are finishing the tasks honestly and completely. As long as you read the instructions and complete the tasks, your HIT will be approved. If you fail these checks, your HIT will be rejected.

 

Risks and benefits. There are no known risks to participation in this study. Other than the payment mentioned, there are also no tangible benefits to you, other than contributing to our knowledge about human reasoning.

 

Confidentiality and use of data. All the information we collect during the course of this research will be processed in accordance with Data Protection Law. In order to safeguard your privacy, we will never share personal information (e.g., your working ID) with anyone outside the research team. Your data will be referred to by a unique participant number rather than by your working ID. However, please note that we will temporarily collect your worker ID to prevent repeated participation. The anonymized data collected during this study will be used for research purposes.

 

What are my data protection rights? The University of Edinburgh is a Data Controller for the information you provide. You have the right to access information stored about you. Your right of access can be exercised in accordance with Data Protection Law. You also have other rights including rights of correction, erasure and objection. For more details, including the right to lodge a complaint with the Information Commissioner’s Office, please visit www.ico.org.uk. Questions, comments, and requests about your personal data can also be sent to the University Data Protection Officer at dpo@ed.ac.uk.

 

Voluntary participation and right to withdraw. Your participation is voluntary, and you may withdraw from the study at any time and for any reason. If you withdraw from the study during or after data gathering, we will delete your data.

 

If you have any questions about what you’ve just read, please feel free to contact us by email at bramleylab@ed.ac.uk. This project has been approved by PPLS Ethics committee. If you have questions or comments regarding your own rights as a participant, they can be contacted at 0131 650 4020 or ppls.ethics@ed.ac.uk.

 

By accepting this HIT, you consent to the following:

 

1. I agree to participate in this study.

2. I confirm that I am at least 18 years old or older. 

3. I confirm that I have read and understood how my data will be stored and used.

4. I understand that I have the right to terminate this session at any point.

Part 2
In another study, we asked participants to come up with questions that would help them to distinguish a voice assistant (such as Siri or Alexa) from an adult. We asked them to imagine that they are sitting in front of a curtain. Behind the curtain, there was either a voice assistant or an adult. Their goal was to find out which it is. They could ask the agent questions, and the agent would provide a written answer. Participants would try to guess the agent's identity by reading the answers.
Below are the questions our participants decided to ask the agent behind the curtain to find out if that was a voice assistant or an adult. 

Please rate how good and effective each question is to figure out the identity of the agents behind the curtain (i.e., to distinguish a voice assistant from an adult). - Can you please tell me what I should do in a breakup with my girlfriend?

In another study, we asked participants to come up with questions that would help them to distinguish a voice assistant (such as Siri or Alexa) from an adult. We asked them to imagine that they are sitting in front of a curtain. Behind the curtain, there was either a voice assistant or an adult. Their goal was to find out which it is. They could ask the agent questions, and the agent would provide a written answer. Participants would try to guess the agent's identity by reading the answers.
Below are the questions our participants decided to ask the agent behind the curtain to find out if that was a voice assistant or an adult. 

Please rate how good and effective each question is to figure out the identity of the agents behind the curtain (i.e., to distinguish a voice assistant from an adult). - What is the most important thing when working with other people?

I decided that the more generic questions (like where can I get something, or static knowledge or mathematical problems) would be best answered by a voice assistant, whereas questions surrounding feelings, emotions, etc would be better provided by the adult. However, a few of these could be best answered by both.

For very straight forward answers such as the math questions, language questions, questions about restaurants or stats of places I feel like the voice assist would be able to answer those questions by combing the internet. I put both for some because some people would know the answer to some of the simpler math, language and questions relating to their home. For answering questions about life or morality I think an adult would have been better, perhaps a bit more nuanced. I don't necessarily think a computer understands the grey areas that life can be. I think it can spit back answers that you ask it but it's not alive and doesn't really have those experiences to pull from (besides what's on the internet or it's programmed to know)

I decided some questions were definitely best answered by the voice assistant if they were technical questions, like some of the math problems and some questions requiring vast knowledge of other countries. I decided questions involving feelings or issues of morality were best answered by an adult, because computers can't feel or make judgements on if something is morally right or wrong.

I focused mostly on whether the agent could reasonably be expected to have an answer to the question (so voice assistants don't have childhood experiences; adults probably can't do complicated math in their head). I also thought about what kind of questions people are likely to ask each agent, and I've seen screenshots of people asking Siri morality questions before.

I assessed each question individually. If it was clearly a question that required human feelings, emotions, or experience I chose towards that side. If it was a question that had a "correct" answer ie. it was addressing factual information I chose that the agent was more likely the best choice (my thinking was that while an adult could also find the answer by various means, the agent would be the quickest way to get the answer). If the question relied on opinion, I also trended toward the adult option.
